		<td><b>rainwarrior</b> [ Fri Dec 19, 2014 6:13 pm ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Re: Which assembler should I be using?</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />My vote is always for ca65. If you're looking for more examples to get started, I wrote one a few months ago: <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=11151" class="postlink">Minimal NES example using ca65</a><br /><br />Assemblers don't usually have a GUI. That's part of an <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Integrated_development_environment" class="postlink">IDE</a>, not the assembler. Tepples already recommended <a href="http://www.nesicide.com/" class="postlink">NESICIDE</a>, if you're looking for an IDE, and it's the only one in existence for NES that I know of. Whether or not you use an IDE, I would strongly recommend that you try to gain some facility with command line tools, though. It's a useful skill for a programmer to have.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


