	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>koitsu</b> [ Tue Dec 30, 2014 12:27 pm ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Re: Which assembler should I be using?</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />Yes, there are people here who use <a href="http://www.villehelin.com/wla.html" class="postlink">WLA DX</a> to do NES development, but it's more intended for other platforms.  The WLA DX documentation is vast and simultaneously horrible (not because of its size, but rather just because the quality and wording is atrocious -- I still have yet to successfully assemble anything with it simply because the documentation is so bad).<br /><br /><a href="https://home.comcast.net/~olimar/NES/" class="postlink">asm6</a> and ca65/cc65 are the most prominent two you'll find mentioned here.<br /><br />ca65 has a significantly higher learning curve and a lot of hullabaloo that I've never felt was necessary (mainly the templating crap), but the majority of folks here prefer it.<br /><br />If you want to use something that has good community support (i.e. people here can help you), use either asm6 or ca65.  If you aren't sure which to try, try both -- they're both standalone programs that don't require installation (you just drop them into a single directory and you're done), so if you don't like one you just delete the folder and that's it.<br /><br />You're going to need to overcome your fear of command-line programs.  And It's a fairly ridiculous fear given the platform you plan on developing for.  You're going to be doing a lot of typing writing assembly code, not a lot of clicking with a mouse.  You can write a Windows batch/cmd file that assembles the program (makes a .NES ROM) <strong>once</strong> and never have to edit it again.  The key part of this paragraph is this: if you're just starting out, you're going to have a single source code file for your entire program, and maybe a single .chr file for your pattern table/graphics and that's about it.  You don't need an IDE for that.  The last thing that should be on your mind is an IDE right now -- what should be on your mind is learning 6502 assembly and learning how the NES actually works (particularly the PPU).

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


