	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">Erockbrox wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">[edit] I just installed Ophis Assembler, but I dislike very much command line programs. Why can't it be a simple GUI program?</div><br />There is not a need for a whole lot of command line programming. Like <strong>koitsu </strong>wrote, it can be a .bat file you edit once.<br /><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">&#91;example for asm6 .bat file&#93;<br />asm6 input.asm output.nes</div><br />Simple enough. You could also drag and drop source files with asm6, but that will produce a .bin by standard.<br />All these preferences like editors, fonts, highlighters and whatnot is a later part of your learning.<br />Notepad for Windows and something to assemble with - that is a great start  <img src="./images/smilies/icon_cool.gif" alt="8-)" title="Cool" />

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>tokumaru</b> [ Tue Dec 30, 2014 3:02 pm ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Re: Which assembler should I be using?</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">Erockbrox wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Why can't it be a simple GUI program?</div><br />GUIs add a lot of bloat to a program that would otherwise perform a simple task (convert source files into binary images). Instead of a standalone small file you end up with something several MBs large that needs to be installed and depends on a bunch of runtime libraries that also need to be downloaded and installed. Sounds awfully unnecessary to me.<br /><br />Just because a program is operated from the command line that doesn't mean you have to type a lot of stuff every time you use it. Like koitsu and mikaelmoizt said, you can create a batch file (a text file with the .bat extension with the commands you want to execute written in it), and simply double click that file every time you need to assemble. Just be sure to put a &quot;pause&quot; command at the end of the batch file to prevent the command window from closing immediately, otherwise you won't be able to read the messages the assembler outputs (such as error messages which really help locating mistakes in your code).

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


