		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Re: Which assembler should I be using?</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">looks like it exports to nes, snes and tons more. Has anyone ever used this before? Anyone have any feedback on this?</div><br />Yes I can. WLA-DX is a pretty nice assembler with tons of features. The 6502 version of it is great, with the exeption that it can't decide between zero-page and absolute addressing for you, so you have to default to one and add &quot;.b&quot; or &quot;.w&quot; suffixes when you use the other (if you don't default you'll have to always use suffixes).<br /><br />Do not use the SPC700 version however, it's buggy as hell and doesn't assemble what you tell it to. The author (Vile Helin) seems not to be working on the assembler anymore and nobody took the development of it, so it seems the project is dead, and that you won't get any bugfixes or updates in the future, which is a problem.<br /><br />Command line programs are pretty much the sole alternative when it comes to compiling programs. I don't remember having any compiler or assembler with GUI, at best you have a GUI who calls the command line program. I personally prefer to use the command line as much as possible, because of it's simplicity and universality (which computer can't have a command line ? Ok, many embedded systems can't, but you see my point).

		

		</td>
	</tr>
